t2161.text: It’s unbelievable to see your entire country on fire. I am shattered to see my country like this, and I’m not even experiencing one-tenth of what others have experienced here with the bushfires.

t2162.text: There is no blue sky. No clouds. Just white, bright sky, and smoke haze. It looks like the apocalypse...

t2163.text: Visibility is so bad that it’s reduced to a couple hundred metres - the length of 4 Olympic swimming pools. I had to get onto the Hume freeway to get to Bunnings, and a large truck carrying hay bales passed me, heading up to the fire regions.

t2164.text: My mum suffered badly with smoke inhalation and was sick in bed. The local Bunnings ran out of P2 filtration masks, so I had to drive 40 mins one way to the bigger Bunnings, & luckily, they just got a shipment in this morning. They can’t keep up with demand.

t2165.text: Thankfully, it is contained, but it’s still burning. Today, my day started like this: the smoke haze put my home city of Melbourne in the hazardous category, with the worst air quality in the world due to the bushfires.

t2166.text: I wanted to share with you what it’s like… Although I’m not in a bushfire region, I live in the north-eastern suburbs of Melbourne, and I am in a heavily bushland area, which a bushfire started here in our nature reserve a couple of weeks ago. (Thread) #AustralianBushfires
